Why is this better than 1D (Sequence)?
Spatial Awareness: The GNN knows which residues are physically close in the epitope, even if they are far apart in the sequence.
Orientation: A 3D GNN can encode the surface geometry (convex/concave) of the epitope, which is critical for CDR-H3 fitting.
Physical Constraints: You can feed the GNN the distances between atoms, helping the model learn "van der Waals" constraints implicitly.
How to get ag_gnn_features?
In a real industry pipeline, you would use a library like PyTorch Geometric to represent the antigen. The GNN takes:
Nodes: Amino acid type + 
 coordinates.
Edges: Vectors pointing from one residue to its 
-nearest neighbors.
