In a de novo design scenario where you only have the antigen (epitope) information and no starting CDR3 template, the problem shifts from "optimization" to "Antigen-to-Sequence Translation." 
Instead of masking an existing sequence, you treat the antigen's 3D/sequence features as a prompt to generate a binder from scratch. 
1. De Novo Design Workflow (Logic)
The core challenge is that ESM-2 is not natively "generative" in a one-shot sense for new binders. In industry, this is typically solved using a Latent Diffusion or Encoder-Decoder approach: 
Antigen Encoding: You pass the antigen epitope through an ESM-2 encoder (1D) or a GNN (3D) to create a "Target Embedding".
CDR3 Generation: You use an Antibody Decoder (like a RoFormer or a custom Transformer) that uses Cross-Attention to "read" the antigen's embedding and generate the CDR3 sequence amino-by-amino.
Scaffold Grafting: The generated CDR3 is then grafted onto a standard human germline framework (e.g., IGHV3-23) to form a complete Fv region. 
